\label{lem: def nu}
	For $(x,y) = ((a,v),(u, av + v^\sharp)) \in G$, we have \[\exp_+(x,y) (s)_{-2} = \nu(u,a,v) s_{2} \mod L_{< 2}.\]
	This scalar $\nu(u,a,v) \in R$ is given by
	\[ u \bar{u} - a\bar{a} T(v,v) + a N(v) + \bar{a} \overline{N(v)} - T(v^\sharp,v^\sharp).\]
	\begin{proof}
		This is a lengthy computation, feasible by hand.
		First, we can extend scalars with a faithfully flat $R'$, in such a way that $R'[u]/(u^2 - u + \alpha) \cong R'[t]/(t^2 - t)$, which can be done by \cite[Theorem 4.1.7]{Michiel2025}.

		Using that $\exp_+(x,y)$ is an automorphism, we obtain
		\[\exp_+(x,y) [t, \bar{t}] = [(T_{(x,y)} t),[x,\bar{t}]] + [[x,t],(T_{x,y} \bar{t})]  + [Q_{(x,y)} t, Q_{(x,y)} \bar{t}] \mod L_{<2}.\]

		One computes that
		\begin{align*}
			[(T_{(x,y)} t),[x,\bar{t}]] + [[x,t],(T_{x,y} \bar{t})] = (t - \bar{t})(a\bar{a}(a\bar{a} - T(v,v)) + a N(v) + \bar{a} \overline{N(v)}).\end{align*}
		One can also show that
		\begin{align*}
			[Q_{(x,y)} t, Q_{(x,y)} \bar{t}] &= (t - \bar{t})( - (a\bar{a})^2 + u \bar{u} - T(v^\sharp,v^\sharp)).
		\end{align*}
	Combining those two yields
	\[ \nu(u,a,v) = u \bar{u} - a\bar{a} T(v,v) + aN(v) + \bar{a} \bar{N(v)} - T(v^\sharp,v^\sharp). \qedhere\]
	\end{proof}

